snippet.textDisplay: Well I’ve looked through the comments and have not seen anyone mentioning this. But you missed a few more aviation things. The AC vents and interior lights are taken directly out of an early 90’s Cessna or something similar. Also, if you look at the dash, all the different boxes housing each instrument and buttons, they each look replaceable because that’s how it is in airplanes, too. They’re meant to be upgraded every few years or so. That’s why there’s 4 screws on each of those “boxes.” That’s also why that row of fuses are there. Oh and also the compass is exactly like what you’d find in a little Cessna or Piper Cub. Good stuff and super quirky. Love it. 🤓

snippet.textDisplay: As a former aircraft electrician, those are actual aircraft circuit breakers. Each are rated at 200% of their indicated amperage value, for a range of seconds (usually between 10-55) before they trip. Thus, if one of those breakers pops out, DO NOT PUSH IT BACK IN, or you'll soon smell smoke and possibly see flames.

snippet.textDisplay: Wow! You opened up the engine bay, yet didn't even mention that the configuration of the engine for this car  is extremely strange for a  mid-engined vehicle; i.e. the "elephant in the room": the engine is transverse mounted in this car! Sure, it wasn't a first as per Vector, but it certainly was not common in the industry at the time. Lancia and Lotus were the prime movers of this layout.
